Date:4/20/2012 10:35:14 AM
From:E_K_S
Hi robert -

Re: Graham Number

I have now been using this as one of my main metrics for new buys. For me it is
a fast and easy 1st screen that I can modify to an EK$ value adjusting for
company specific factors and events. I have found that I have made money with
some of the most boring (off the radar) stocks so OMG may be a good value pick
especially if/when the semiconductor cycle picks up (as Intel recently
described in their 2012 forward look presentation).

The key is to spread your bets around and not to necessarily focus on leading
edge technology products but rather support type components (ie. capacitors,
connectors, simple test equipment) that does not change too much from each new
development cycle.

I have found more companies in the Oil & Gas sector that sell below their GN
but have not really screened too many in other sectors. From the list in the
article, Cascade Corp. (CASC)is one that pops out for me. Their GN value is
$49.28 (article uses BV rather than TBV but even w/ a TBV at $20.07/share the
stock sells below it's GN). I have added CASC to my watch list. Their 3%
dividend is a bonus too.

As has been pointed out in several comments regarding the Graham Number, there
are specific minimum criteria that companies must meet to generate a GN that
means something. First, EPS must be positive and reflect at least a 10 year
stream. I will let some companies get a pass if EPS show a one time loss that
might be a company specific issue that is easily explained. Use TBV not BV when
possible as BV contains Goodwill charges that really add no $ value to the
enterprise. PE s/d be 15 or less but I will use up to 20 if that number
reflects the industry average. Finally, the GN has worked well for me when I
initiate a "Buy" but almost always has gotten me out too early when I use it to
calculate a fair value market "Sell" price.

Therefore, when the GN equals or exceeds the market price, I remove the stock
from my GN watch list and watch it more closely for company and/or industry
specific news. I watch it with a short leash and might begin to scale out of
the position w/ one of my first three sells. Many of these GN finds will and
have become multi baggers (ie CBI is one I own) so keep at least a 1/3 position
in your basket to obtain the higher valuation the market is providing during
this peak cycle run.

I continue to fine tune my use of the GN. I am not so sure what will happen to
GN valuations if/when the FED starts to raise interest rates but I expect more
refinment will be required.

EKS
